result.execSummary:
Jean T Alexander was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Jean T Alexander was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Judge Koschnick presiding for Branch III Intake: 
case called at 1:34pm. [MK] 
Defendant Jean T Alexander in court, in custody.  Public Service Prosecutor Melanie Flint appears for the State of Wisconsin.
Service of the Extradition Complaint is admitted; reading is waived.
Extradition Rights given.  Ms. Alexander indicates that she generally understands the extradition procedure.
Right to counsel given. Ms. Alexander waives this right.  The Court accepts the waiver and finds that Ms. Alexander is competent to represent herself. 
Ms. Alexander indicates that she is waiving extradtion rights and that she is prepared to sign the Waiver of Extradition form. 
Ms. Alexander signs the forms after being given the oath by the Court. 
The Court finds that Ms. Alexander is waiving her extradition rights freely, voluntarily and intelligently; the Court accepts the Waiver of Extradition. 
The Court indicates that the Texas authorities are to be contacted so that arrangements to transport Ms. Alexander begin promptly. 
Deputy Wegner indicates that the Waiver of Extradition form will be faxed from the Jail to the Texas authorities immediately after this hearing. 
recess 1:42pm.
